issue_body:
Sorry, please test this program first before close this issue.
No matter the thread use the function 'getm' or not,  If this function was invoked, all threads would be binded on the same core of CPU.  You can move the line: matrix<double, 3, 3> w = getm() * getm(); into body of thread, the result is same. But when using declaration 1, the usage of CUP is normal.
The key problem is not about the body of thread, the body in thread could be anything. I think it may be because of memory management of matrix.

--------------------------------------------------------------------
#include < thread>
#include <dlib/matrix.h>

using namespace std;
using namespace dlib;

//const matrix<double, 3, 3> getm() {    // declaration 1
const matrix<double, 3, 0> getm() {      // declaration 2
    return matrix<double, 3, 3>();
}

int main(int argc, char* argv[])
{
    int threads = 4;
    matrix<double, 3, 3> w = getm() * getm();
    std::thread ths[threads];
    for (int i = 0; i < threads; i++) {
        ths[i] = std::thread([]() {
            int a = 1;
            for (;;) {
                a = (a * std::rand() + 1234) % 1000;
            }
        });
    }
    for (int i = 0; i < threads; i++) {
        ths[i].join();
    }
    exit (0);
}
-------------------------------------------------

As declaration 2, the return type is matrix<double, 3, 0>, When this program is running, all threads run on only one core of CPU, in other words, One core is 100% usage, others is free.
As declaration 1, I change the return type to matrix<double, 3, 3>, all cores of CPU is 100% usage, this is my expected result.
I do this test, because this problem exists in shape_predictor.
In function 'find_affine_transform' (geometry/point_transforms.h),
the line: const matrix<double,2,3> m = Q*pinv(P);
The matrix P is defined as matrix<double,3,0>, so return type of template function pinv is matrix<double,3,0>.

* **Version**: 19.9
* **Where did you get dlib**: github
* **Platform**: ubuntu 16.04 64
* **Compiler**: gcc 5.4.0

I've developed a handy utility which looks like @decorator, but pre-resolves arguments before passing them to the wrapper function (using https://docs.python.org/2/library/inspect.html#inspect.getcallargs).

It's very useful when you need to decorate many functions, without knowing it advanced if they'll be passed arguments by position (<*args>) or by keywords (<**kwargs>). Since incoming arguments are normalized in a simple dict, you can inspect and modify them freely. 

I used it to automatically inject or commit/rollback SQL sessions which travelled through program, for example.

Below is an example of use.

Would you be OK for me to prepare a pull request including that utility next to the standard "decorator".

```
        @resolving_decorator
        def inject_session(func, **all_kwargs):
            if not all_kwargs["session"]:
                all_kwargs["session"] = "<SESSION>"
            return func(**all_kwargs)
        
        @inject_session
        def myfunc(session):
            return session
        
        assert myfunc(None) == myfunc(session=None) == "<SESSION>"
        assert myfunc("<stuff>") == myfunc(session="<stuff>") == "<stuff>"
```

