I get the following error...

> Error: binance order price exceeds allowed price precision or invalid, use this.priceToPrecision (symbol, amount) {"code":-1013,"msg":"Filter failure: PRICE_FILTER"}

when attempting to create Stop Loss with the following code:

```
function precisionRound(num, precision) {
  precision = Math.pow(10, precision)
  return Math.round(num * precision) / precision
}

var buyLimitPrice = precisionRound((lowestPriceExchange.askPrice * 1.005), 8);
const stopPrice = precisionRound((buyLimitPrice * 0.9), 8);
const limitPrice = precisionRound((buyLimitPrice * 0.89), 8);

lowestPriceExchange.exchange.createOrder(coinPair, 'stop_loss_limit', 'sell', quantity, limitPrice, { 'stopPrice' : stopPrice })

```

Initially I had
`
const stopPrice = buyLimitPrice * 0.9;
const limitPrice = buyLimitPrice * 0.89;
`

and got that error above, so I interpreted the error to mean I didn't have the correct number of decimal places, which is why I added the rounding function with a precision of 8 places after decimal point. 

But now even with the rounding function, I still get the same error and struggling to identify what the root issue is.

I notice that if a try to protect an entire blueprint with `@jwt_required`, than also the `OPTIONS` method is protected. 

`OPTIONS` method should not include crendetials, see [here](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/15734031/why-does-the-preflight-options-request-of-an-authenticated-cors-request-work-in).

The `@jwt_required` decorator should ignore `OPTIONS` like in `flask_login`:


```python
    @wraps(func)
    def decorated_view(*args, **kwargs):
        if request.method in EXEMPT_METHODS:
            return func(*args, **kwargs)
        elif current_app.login_manager._login_disabled:
            return func(*args, **kwargs)
        elif not current_user.is_authenticated:
            return current_app.login_manager.unauthorized()
        return func(*args, **kwargs)
    return decorated_view
```

where `EXEMPT_METHODS=set(["OPTIONS"])`!

I could fix this and create a pull request if this is not a desired choice!

