I was wondering what the semantic of `py::init<Ts...>` are. Say I have a type `T` that takes a constructor argument of type `U` by value. Will this result in a move?

Here's an example from my project. A type `subnet` that takes a type `address` by value. The ctor of `subnet` has the signature `subnet(address, uint8_t)`.

```cpp
    .def("__init__",
         [](subnet& instance, address& addr, uint8_t length) {
           new (&instance) subnet{std::move(addr), length};
         })
```

Is this equivalent to `py::init<address, uint8_t>`? Essentially, I wonder whether you perform a `move` or copy on the call side, and whether I should ensure no extra copying by taking a non-const lvalue for `address` in the lambda above.

Two related questions:
1. How do I specify default arguments in constructors?
2. How do I support move-only types in constructors?

For (2), I have a class `context` that takes a `configuration` object by value in the ctor:

```cpp
  class context {
  public:
    context(configuration = {}); // configuration has no copy constructor
  };

  py::class_<context>(m, "Context")
    //.def(py::init<>()) // compile error: attempts to invoke copy ctor
    .def("__init__",
     [](context& instance, configuration& cfg) { // works, but how to specify a default argument?
       new (&instance) context{std::move(cfg)};
     })
```

(Is there a mailing list or better place for such questions? I couldn't find it in the manual.)

## Issue description

Say, I have a pure abstract class (Ancestor).
I implemented a sub class inheriting it (Parent).
For testing purpose, I've implemented another sub class inheriting Parent (Child).

When I create a python binding for a function `std::shared_ptr<Ancestor> CreateChild() { return std::make_shared<Child>(); }` as a name `create_child()`, I expected that

```
create_child().function
```

calls a function of the Child, but by unknown reasons, a function of the class Parent was called, and finally SEGV occurs.


## Reproducible example code

```cpp
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

#include <memory>

namespace py = pybind11;

class Ancestor {
public:
    virtual ~Ancestor() = default;
    virtual const std::string& name() = 0;
};

class Parent : public Ancestor {
public:
    Parent() : name_("Parent") {}
    const std::string& name() override { return name_; }
private:
    std::string name_;
};

class Child : public Parent {
public:
    Child() : name_("Child") {}
    const std::string& name() override { return name_; }
private:
    std::string name_;
};

std::shared_ptr<Ancestor> CreateChild() { return std::make_shared<Child>(); }

std::string GetChildName() {
    std::shared_ptr<Ancestor> a = std::make_shared<Child>();
    return a->name();
}

PYBIND11_MODULE(example, m) {
    py::class_<Ancestor>(m, "Ancestor").def_property_readonly("name", &Ancestor::name);
    m.def("create_child", &CreateChild);
    m.def("get_child_name", &GetChildName);
}
